    "summary": "JEROEN BERKVENS' documentary debut was A SKIN TOO FEW \u2013 THE DAYS OF NICK DRAKE; a film that \u201cbeautifully evokes the enduring appeal of English singer-songwriter Nick Drake\u201d according to Variety magazine. Described \"a cinematic tone poem as much as a biography\u201d by the NYTimes when it got a theatrical release in the US. Universal/Island added the film to the box with Drake's collected works. \n\nAlso MIRROR OF TIME; a series on non-narrative documentaries & A LAWYER\u2019S STORY; in which a notorious defence criminal lawyer reshapes his life after a bomb attack, as well as episodes for several tv-documentary series are among Jeroen's list of work as director.\n\nJIMMY ROSENBERG - THE FATHER, THE SON & THE TALENT is his follow-up in a line of films that depict stories about the burden of being gifted. It was awarded a GRAND PRIX in Poland, USA & Canada, in the Netherlands it won a \u2018Golden Calf\u2019.\n\nThe film PARADISO shows Amsterdam\u2019s pop temple as seen from the perspective of several performing artists. It won the Grand Prize at the Jecheon Music & Film Festival in Korea.\n\nOTHER OCCUPATIONS\n\nFrom 2001 till 2010 Jeroen was appointed to teach documentary directing at the Academy of Arts in Breda, the same institute where he graduated in 1993 with LET ME HAVE IT ALL; a roadmovie-like search for funk legend Sly Stone, which received an ARTE award for best European student film.\n\nJeroen also teached, was coaching filmstudents or gave masterclasses at various other educations, like the IDFA Summerschool 2009 & '19, Sandberg Institute, for Screen Training in Ireland 2008, in Istanbul for Ministry of Foreign Affairs in 2012 and at UvA master Mediastudies in 2014, '15 & '19. \nHe led documentary filmworkshops at IDFA in 2004, and in Romania for Aristoteles Workshop in 2011, '12, '13 & '18.\n\nSince 2010 Jeroen is appointed to the Netherlands Film Academy in Amsterdam, teaching documentary directing.\n\nJeroen occasionally was a producer for film- & tvprojects. Among them; Mark de Cloe's BOY MEETS GIRL STORIES - 33 short film poems depicting 'the lover'.\nLIFE IS BEAUTIFUL, consists of 30 mini-films, and is a follow up to the former, co-directed by Jeroen alongside de Cloe.\n\nJeroen also worked as a commissioning editor for documentary series at PBS Humanist Broadcasting (HUMAN).",
